{
  "doc_id": "38351",
  "text": "A number of proteins and associated factors maintain the dynamic nature of MTs [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Classical microtubule-associated proteins (MAPs) perform a wide range of functions to regulate MT dynamics for properly organizing and remodeling the neuronal cytoskeleton [CITATION_3] . All MAP1 proteins play a role in MT stabilization and their transfection in heterologous cells results in the formation of MT bundles [CITATION_4] . MAP1 family, particularly MAP1B has distinct roles in MT-based processes such as, neuronal migration, growth cone turning and actin-based processes such as dendritic spine maturation [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Although several MAPs have been identified, the mechanisms underlying coordinated regulation of axonal cytoskeleton with synaptic growth remain to be fully elucidated. The only Drosophila homolog of vertebrate MAP1B, Futsch, is necessary for dendritic, axonal and synaptic MT organization and growth [CITATION_8] . Futsch controls neuromuscular junction (NMJ) bouton growth through regulation of synaptic MTs . Recent studies on Drosophila futsch have uncovered its role in stabilizing active zones (AZs) by reinforcing their link with the underlying MT cytoskeleton and in regulating neurotransmitter release at the NMJ [CITATION_9] as well as activity dependent AZ remodeling of photoreceptor synapses [CITATION_10] .",
